  <chapter id="generaltest"><title>General Orca Functionality</title>

    <para>The tests in this section are meant to test general Orca
      functionality that should be work regardless of the application
      in use.</para>

    <section id="interoperabilitytest"><title>Interaction with Other ATs</title>
      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that Orca does not
        can adverse effects on other assistive technologies that may be
	running, and that other assitive technologies do not adversely
	effect Orca.</para>

    </section>

    <section id="flatreviewtest"><title>Flat Review</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that the Orca flat
        review functionality is working as expected.  This includes
	making sure the various keystrokes work and produce the
	desired results.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Test basic flat review navigation.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gnome terminal and type "ls".  Use the number 7 on the numpad to move up by line until you reach the menubar.  At this point press numpad 6 repeatedly to move across the menubar.</para>
        <para>&tresult; While moving up with 7 each line of the terminal window should be read.  While moving right across the menubar each word of each menu item should be read.  After finishing, reverse this process using KP4 and KP9 for word and line respectively.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Test the performance of mouse clicks in flat review.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gnome terminal and review to the top of the screen with numpad 7.  At this point, move to the right with  KP3 until you reach the e of the edit menu.  While on the "e" press KP/ to perform a left mouse click.</para>
        <para>&tresult; While moving up the screen each line should be read.  While moving right with KP3 each letter should be read.  When you press KP/, the edit menu should open.</para>

    </section>

    <section id="learnmodetest"><title>Learn Mode</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that the Orca
        Learn Mode functionality works as expected for both the
        keyboard and braille, including entering and exiting Learn
        Mode.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Test the learn mode to assure that orca speaks useful information for each orca keystroke.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Press insert+f1 to enable learn mode.  Press all keys on the numpad both with and without the orca modifier key (usually insert).  After testing all keys, press escape to exit learn mode.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Listen to the speech output associated with each keypress.  Orca should give meaningful output describing what the key does.  This information should also appear on the braille display.  If information is un-clear a bug should be filed.</para>

    </section>

    <section id="whereamitest"><title>Where Am I?</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that the Orca
        Where Am I functionality produces the desired
        information.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should give a top down summary of the current multipage dialog.  </para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open up terminal, open the "edit current preferences dialog", tab once to the first control in the first page, and  press KP enter.  </para>
        <para>&tresult;  Orca should speak the following information in the following order.  App name, dialog name, page name, control name with label. </para>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should give a top down summary of the current document with focus.  </para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open up gedit, open two documents and press KP enter.  </para>
        <para>&tresult;  Orca should speak the following information in the following order.  App name, Document name, control name (ie edidt), statusbar information such as the current line in the document. </para>

        <para>&tprocedure; Open up gedit, modify one of the documents, press CTRL+q to exit  and press KP enter.  </para>
        <para>&tresult;  Orca should speak the following information in the following order.  App name, Dialog title, control name with lable . </para>
    </section>

    <section id="sayalltest"><title>Say All</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that the Orca Say
        All functionality behaves appropriately for contiguous
        document content, including GEdit, StarOffice, etc.  The Say
        All tests for flat review of dialogs are in the Flat Review
        section.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Test say-all in gedit.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open a long document and position the cursor at the top.  Press numpad+plus to start reading the document.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should read the document from beginning to end honoring the current punctuation setting.  The document should also be read with a natural flow IE sentences should flow smoothly from one to the next.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Test say'all;s character positioning  in gedit.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open a long document and position the cursor at the beginning of the 4th line.  Press numpad+plus to start reading the document.  Press CTRL to stop reading about 3/4 the way through the document.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should read the document from beginning to end honoring the current punctuation setting.  The document should also be read with a natural flow IE sentences should flow smoothly from one to the next. When CTRL is pressed, the cursor should be placed at the beginning of the last word spoken.</para>

        <para>&tgoal; Test say-all in Star Office Writer.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open the orca documentation HTML file and position the cursor at the top.  Press numpad+plus to start reading the document.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should read the document from beginning to end honoring the current punctuation setting.  The document should also be read with a natural flow IE sentences should flow smoothly from one to the next.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Test say-all in Firefox.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open live.gnome.org/Orca and position the cursor at the top of the page.  Press numpad+plus to start reading the document.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should read the page from beginning to end honoring the current punctuation setting.  The document should also be read with a natural flow IE sentences should flow smoothly from one to the next.  THe word link should also be spoken after each link.  </para>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should read a dialog box from top to bottom.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and press CTRL=O to open the file open dialog.  When the dialog is open press SayAll (KP+).</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should read the entire dialog from top to bottom.</para>

    </section>

    <section id="verbalizedpunctest"><title>Verbalized Punctuation</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that the Orca
        Verbalized Punctuation functionality provides the desired
	output for the various verbalized punctuation settings.</para>

    </section>

    <section id="verbalizedlinktest"><title>Verbalized Links</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that the Orca
        Verbalized Link functionality provides the desired
	output for the various verbalized link settings.</para>

    </section>

    <section id="verbalizedcapstest"><title>Verbalized Caps</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that the Orca
        Verbalized Caps functionality provides the desired output for
        the various verbalized capitalization settings.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Test the pitch change option.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Be sure that orca is set to change the pitch of a letter when the letter is encountered.  In Gedit, type the letters a through f as sets of each letter.  The first being in upercase and the second lower case.  For example: Aa Bb and so on.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When arrowing through the letters, the first should be at a higher pitch than the second.</para>

        <para>&tgoal; Test the speak caps option.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Be sure that orca is set to speak caps when a character is capitalized when the letter is encountered.  In Gedit, type the letters a through f as sets of each letter.  The first being in upercase and the second lower case.  For example: Aa Bb and so on.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When arrowing through the letters, the first should be preceded by "cap" and the second should not.</para>
            </section>
    <section id="spellingmodetest"><title>Spelling Mode</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that the Orca
        Spelling Mode functionality provides the desired output for
        the various spelling mode settings.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Test the performance of orca's spell word functionality.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and type a sentence.  Move from one word to the next with CTRL+right arrow and double click KP5 very quickly.  Wait a few seconds after the double press of KP5 and Press KP5 again quickly 3 times.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When doubleclicking KP5 on the first word the word should be spelled honoring the speak capitalization setting.  All Other words should just be spelled.  When the last word is reached, it should also be spelled not including the period.  If the caret happens to be on a space orca should just say space.  When triple clicking KP5 the word should be spelled using military spelling.</para>
    </section>

    <section id="textattributestest"><title>Text Attributes</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that Orca
        accurately provides text attribute (e.g., font, bolding, etc.)
        information when requested by the user.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Test the speak attributes hot key in star office writer.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Type 3 words in star office writer.  The first should be in the default size and style.  The second should have both the point size and font family changed.  The third should be bolded and underlined.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When pressing insert+f at the beginning of the first word, you should hear, the default family and size.  At the beginning of the second word, you should hear the new family and size.  At the beginning of the third word you should hear, the default family and size followed by the words "bold underline".</para>
            <para>&tgoal; Test the speak attributes hot key in gedit.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Type 3 words in gedit.  The first should be in the default size and style.  The second should have both the point size and font family changed.  The third should be bolded and underlined.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When pressing insert+f at the beginning of the first word, you should hear, the default family and size.  At the beginning of the second word, you should hear the new family and size.  At the beginning of the third word you should hear, the default family and size followed by the words "bold underline".</para>
</section>

    <section id="keywordechotest"><title>Key and Word Echo</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to ensure that Orca works
        accurately with the various key and word echo settings.</para>

      <section><title>Simple Typing of Words</title>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should speak words as they are typed.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Type a line of 10 words each followed by spaces.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When the space is typed after each word, the word should be spoken.</para>
      </section>
      <section><title>Typing Words with Punctuation</title>
        <para>&tgoal; Determine if orca speaks the word when a boundary is reached.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; type a line of 10 words, the first 5 followed by a period and the second 5 followed by a comma.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When the period or comma is typed the word should be spoken.  When a space is typed after the punctuation mark the word should not be spoken again.</para>
      </section>
      <section><title>Typing Alphanumeric characters</title>
        <para>&tgoal; Determine if orca speaks characters as they are typed.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; type a line of 10 characters containing letters, numbers, and punctuation marks.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When each character is typed, it should be spoken.</para>

      </section>
      <section><title>Typing Alphanumeric characters with modifiers</title>
        <para>&tgoal; Determine if orca handles combinations of characters and modifiers correctly as they are typed.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and press CTRL+o.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should say "control o" before reading the file open dialog.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and press alt+f.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should say "alt f" before reading the file menu information.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Press insert+space to bring up the orca configuration UI..</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should say "insert space" before reading the dialog.</para>

      </section>
      <section><title>function key echo test </title>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should speak function keys as they are pressed.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and press f10.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should say "f 10" before speaking the focus in the menubar.</para>
                <para>&tgoal; Orca should speak function keys along with modifiers as they are pressed.</para>
	        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and press shift+f10.</para>
	        <para>&tresult; Orca should say "shift f 10" before speaking the focus in the menubar.</para>

      </section>
      <section><title>lock key echo test </title>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should speak lock keys as they are pressed as well as state.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Press caps lock and num lock several times.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should say the key name followed by the state of that key (on or off).  For example, "caps lock on" or "num lock on"</para>
      </section>
      <section><title>action key echo test </title>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should speak location information after delete is pressed.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and type a line of text.  Press home to return to the beginning of the line and press delete untul all characters have been deleted.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When each character is deleted the next character on the line should be spoken.  </para>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should speak updated information after backspace is pressed.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and type a line of text.  Press backspace until all characters have been deleted.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When each character is deleted the previous character on the line should be spoken.  </para>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should speak location information after home and end are pressed.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and type a line of text.  Press home to return to the beginning of the line and press end  to move to the end of the line.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When these keys are pressed the character under the cursor should be spoken preceeded by the key name.  This includes spaces.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Orca should speak location information after page up and page down are pressed.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and open a long document.  Press CTRL+home to return to the beginning of the line and press page down several times to move to the next pages of the document.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When these keys are pressed the line under the cursor should be spoken preceeded by the key name.  This includes spaces.  When the end of the document is reached nothing should be spoken.  Repeat this test with page up expecting the same results.  </para>

      </section>

    </section>

    <section id="brailletest"><title>Braille</title>

      <para>The tests in this section are to make sure that Orca does
        the right thing with respect to spaces and indentation on the
	braille display and with respect to the various braille
	spacing and indentation settings.</para>

    </section>
